186
00:24:48,126 --> 00:24:50,068
And when we talk about code compliance,

187
00:24:50,957 --> 00:24:52,839
We're not talking just about building code.

188
00:24:53,259 --> 00:24:55,241
We're also talking about accessibility code.

189
00:24:55,701 --> 00:24:57,463
We're talking about energy codes as well.

190
00:24:58,564 --> 00:25:15,118
So this particular option, what it would involve, if you imagine yourself walking into that existing building, we have to replace the entirety of the mechanical system, the entirety of the electrical system, because those do not meet current energy codes.

191
00:25:15,998 --> 00:25:18,942
so lighting outlets need to be replaced.

192
00:25:19,943 --> 00:25:31,975
When we move to the structural code, this is where we actually have to put in seismic braces to brace the existing structural frame in a way to bring it up to code again.

193
00:25:32,876 --> 00:25:36,100
In order to do that, we will have to demolish existing walls

194
00:25:37,081 --> 00:25:45,188
And for the purposes of this particular option, what we're dictated to do is actually build those same walls that we have to demolish to put a brace in back in the same exact place.

195
00:25:45,708 --> 00:25:52,895
That we are not allowed to reconfigure any of the interior space here unless it's associated with meeting, say, accessibility requirements.

196
00:25:53,775 --> 00:25:58,758
So toilet rooms that are not currently ADA or MAAB compliant.

197
00:25:58,858 --> 00:26:04,100
That's American Disabilities Association and the Massachusetts Architectural Access Board.

198
00:26:05,101 --> 00:26:12,064
If we have toilet rooms that are not compliant with those accessibility requirements, we'd have to potentially modify the walls in those spaces.

199
00:26:12,835 --> 00:26:18,503
The same for the lecture halls that have tiered floors that have no ramps to the upper levels.

200
00:26:19,184 --> 00:26:24,412
We potentially have to decrease seating capacity in those rooms to be able to insert

201
00:26:24,893 --> 00:26:30,200
either a ramp or potentially a limited use elevator to get up to those back elevations.

202
00:26:30,220 --> 00:26:35,106
So there are some modifications, but we're not allowed to make programmatic modifications to the building.

203
00:26:35,988 --> 00:26:43,177
If we just keep going on the notion of what we're fixing though, the exterior envelope of this building is completely not compliant with energy code.

204
00:26:43,996 --> 00:27:03,525
So that means that we would be replacing all the exterior fenestration, the windows, the doors, as well as adding insulation to the exterior walls, either by adding something to the exterior or to the interior, a complete re-roofing, replacement of insulation to match what we need to comply with energy code.

205
00:27:04,305 --> 00:27:07,107
So really a complete reskinning of the entirety of the building.

206
00:27:07,868 --> 00:27:26,240
And even when we move out to the site, the parking lot that currently have accessible spaces, but they don't have an accessible path from those spaces up to the building, nor an accessible cross slope where the parking spaces are, all that would have to be repaved, regraded to be able to correct that.

207
00:27:26,895 --> 00:27:37,612
So when we look at this dollar value of $437 million, it is a large sum, but it is because there is so much that needs to be fixed with the existing building just as is.

208
00:27:38,885 --> 00:27:54,948
And the important thing to remember with this $437 million is that unless this code repair upgrade option met the educational plan for the project that was developed by the district, none of that would be reimbursable by the MSBA.

209
00:27:54,988 --> 00:27:59,089
That would be entirely on the city of Medford taxpayers to fund the cost of this.

210
00:28:00,549 --> 00:28:05,370
And this, the code repair upgrade does not meet the educational plan that has been

211
00:28:06,993 --> 00:28:13,959
all the way through in terms of various aspects of the educational plan, there is not alignment here with what the scope of renovations would be.

212
00:28:14,759 --> 00:28:26,989
Just starting from the baseline that there is 522,000 square feet here to meet the educational plan, there is more than another 100,000 square feet of space beyond that that's needed.

213
00:28:27,429 --> 00:28:34,495
But even in that space that exists, there are many things about it that are not acceptable right now from an educational plan standpoint.

214
00:28:36,143 --> 00:28:38,388
So that is our code upgrade option.

215
00:28:38,428 --> 00:28:46,185
Again, this is a baseline that's here for a general understanding of what is involved with repairing and upgrading the building.

216
00:28:48,108 --> 00:28:53,611
So alternative B.1.2 was the first of our addition renovation options.

217
00:28:54,752 --> 00:29:08,179
And this option was selected by the building committee really with the understanding that it was one of the options that preserved as much of the existing building structure as possible.

218
00:29:09,039 --> 00:29:16,203
And that's important from a sustainability environmental perspective because it's trying to leverage the embodied carbon

219
00:29:17,083 --> 00:29:18,845
that is within that existing structure.

220
00:29:18,865 --> 00:29:29,213
And so that embodied carbon, when we use that term, what we're saying is that back in 1970, when this building was built, there was a lot of energy expended.

221
00:29:29,553 --> 00:29:36,799
There was a lot of carbon put into the atmosphere in the creation of the concrete frame, and there is steel frame as well in this existing building.

222
00:29:37,486 --> 00:29:40,787
Um, and what we don't want to do is just necessarily throw all that away.

223
00:29:40,807 --> 00:29:48,629
Um, and so this, this, um, option is looking to preserve as much of that as possible, um, in the future building moving forward.

224
00:29:49,129 --> 00:30:00,933
Um, there is square footage that is added to this building as well, um, which is in the form of two stories, um, up above, um, both the central B wing, um, as well as the D wing, which is where the existing.

225
00:30:01,701 --> 00:30:07,316
cafeterias are in a portion of the V wing as well, the vocational wing off to the east.

226
00:30:08,813 --> 00:30:27,026
But this option does have the ability, even though this is reusing the footprint of the existing building, we would have the option, the opportunity here and would be reconfiguring the interior space of the building in a significant way so that we can meet the educational plan.

227
00:30:27,046 --> 00:30:37,213
So that's a key distinction between this option where it looks a lot like, if I flip back to the code repair option, you can see in both the plan and that three-dimensional

228
00:30:37,758 --> 00:30:46,415
diagram, that there's a lot of similarities, other than the fact that we're building up with new addition space here, again, to meet that larger square footage of what we're looking for.

229
00:30:48,546 --> 00:30:52,089
Just some other sort of salient points here as we go through.

230
00:30:52,970 --> 00:31:00,216
This is one of the options that is currently envisioned to have 56 modular classrooms required to build it.

231
00:31:01,097 --> 00:31:06,602
And that's really because the fact that we're building right on top of where everybody is.

232
00:31:06,642 --> 00:31:12,387
So this would be a very time-consuming way of sort of moving around the existing building

233
00:31:13,388 --> 00:31:19,556
Taking over a section of it, renovating it, and then letting students and faculty occupy it.

234
00:31:20,277 --> 00:31:26,786
But while each section is under construction, we will need modular classrooms to be able to give them some place to teach and learn.

235
00:31:28,094 --> 00:31:40,546
And so the number 56 modular classrooms is really driven by whenever we're touching the C wing or the B wing is where we have our highest density of academic classrooms that we have to replicate.

236
00:31:41,326 --> 00:31:48,633
Also worth keeping in mind that when we are touching the vocational wing that there's a considerable impact to students in that wing.

237
00:31:48,673 --> 00:31:49,955
In some cases we can

238
00:31:50,750 --> 00:31:56,819
build like a double size modular classroom to allow students and teachers to work in those spaces.

