01:00:57,812 --> 01:01:03,035
Can you talk about how the maybe why that is so much especially with it as it relates to the height of the building?

476
01:01:03,635 --> 01:01:05,696
Because I know we've talked about that in some other meetings that we've had.

477
01:01:05,716 --> 01:01:07,037
Yep.

478
01:01:08,573 --> 01:01:20,577
So when we go above four or five stories, it's actually it's tied to the height of the highest level above grade in terms of when it rises up.

479
01:01:20,657 --> 01:01:22,717
So sometimes it can be triggered at four stories.

480
01:01:22,758 --> 01:01:24,278
Sometimes it's triggered at five stories.

481
01:01:25,158 --> 01:01:30,780
But there's a premium on the construction costs that's related to the high rise buildings in the building code.

482
01:01:31,750 --> 01:01:45,383
which requires us to put in, just as any sort of high-rise office building, it's trying to provide additional life safety improvements for the occupants, in this case, the students and the teachers within the building.

483
01:01:46,444 --> 01:01:52,350
And so, for instance, there has to be an improved smoke evacuation system within the stairwells.

484
01:01:52,390 --> 01:01:54,392
There's something that's called a fire command center.

485
01:01:54,809 --> 01:01:59,952
that we have to build into the first floor of the building and provide access to all those different smoke controls.

486
01:02:00,573 --> 01:02:11,500
And then we end up having to make the building itself a little bit more robust in terms of the stair towers to make sure that they're more solid and able to withstand impact.

487
01:02:12,040 --> 01:02:16,103
A lot of these code implications came into play after the World Trade Center.

488
01:02:16,938 --> 01:02:26,124
And so that's what's driving a lot of the thought process behind sort of these building code improvements and sort of cost premiums that would come into play.

